<br>
First things first, you have a company which is providing a service; it is your responsibility to provide a feasible and effective customer service. Now if this was only Verant that would be one thing, but we are talking about a major corporation here which some of you may know as Sony. They fail in every way to provide such a service to the public, a service I might add each and every one of us is paying for. You’re not paying to play the game here people, no in fact your RENTING property. When it’s all said and done that’s exactly what it boils down to; renting storage space on Verant/Sonys system.<br>
Back to my point, you’re paying for a service and regardless of how much money you pay the company is obligated by not only moral standards but local/state/federal standards to accompany such services with a proper customer service. <br>
<br>
You as the consumer also have the right not to support the service, so it’s a two way street here. When people realize how poor the support is and refuse to pay, then and only then will a company change. Look at PoP, I recall nearly 4 years ago Verant was so adamant of never allowing such an idea to surface, years later once they start to lose customers to boredom and other games they’ve reneged on their promise that they would not allow gates to exist, it would hurt the integrity of the game.<br>
<br>
Personally I feel if you’re providing a service you should bend over backwards for your customers, what ever did happen to the saying the customers always right? Oh, that’s right two many assholes in the world now who abused that policy; forcing companies to make a change. One dollar or three thousand, it’s still a service your paying for, making a company liable to particular regulations and standards, the problem is getting the right agencies to enforce their own policies. This is more in tune to your “realistic approach” you may seek Tat.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Balrak<br>
Don't make me go midevil on your hiny!<br>
